00:23:00.695 --> 00:23:03.050
AUDIENCE: Could you speak
about the challenges

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:05.270
of drilling wells in Kenya?

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:07.187
In particular, what
type of material

00:23:07.187 --> 00:23:08.270
do you need to go through?

00:23:08.270 --> 00:23:11.110
How difficult is the
material to penetrate?

00:23:11.110 --> 00:23:13.907
How deep do you
typically have to go?

00:23:13.907 --> 00:23:14.990
How large are these wells?

00:23:14.990 --> 00:23:18.520
And what kind of water flow
can you expect out one?

00:23:18.520 --> 00:23:20.192
So what are those challenges?

00:23:20.192 --> 00:23:22.400
SABORE OLE OYIE: According
to the hydrological survey

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:23.980
that we have done,
because we have

00:23:23.980 --> 00:23:26.570
to go through a
hydrological survey,

00:23:26.570 --> 00:23:29.150
and the hydrological
survey has to be approved

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:35.000
by the government as
a registered engineer.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:38.980
And we went through that
and we got the report.

00:23:38.980 --> 00:23:42.460
And the maximum-- the
deepest maximum we can go

00:23:42.460 --> 00:23:49.310
is 250 meters, and the
minimum is 120 meters.

00:23:49.310 --> 00:23:51.820
And, according to his
report, that there

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:56.980
was enough water that it can
produce around 8,000 liters

00:23:56.980 --> 00:23:57.640
in one hour.

00:23:57.640 --> 00:23:58.572
AUDIENCE: Wow.

00:23:58.572 --> 00:24:00.980
SABORE OLE OYIE: So
there was enough water.

00:24:00.980 --> 00:24:03.450
And the other challenge
is also to be approved

00:24:03.450 --> 00:24:10.380
by the government to be
able to get an organization

00:24:10.380 --> 00:24:12.040
to drill the boreholes.

00:24:12.040 --> 00:24:17.070
And, as we don't have our own
company that drills the well,

00:24:17.070 --> 00:24:19.890
we have to find out
the companies that

00:24:19.890 --> 00:24:23.550
are really experienced--
there are a lot of shady work

00:24:23.550 --> 00:24:25.250
that you can find everywhere.

00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:30.040
So we have to be very keen
on looking for the best

00:24:30.040 --> 00:24:32.030
company that can
drill the boreholes.

00:24:32.030 --> 00:24:35.770
And we just pay them, they bring
all the material that we need.

00:24:35.770 --> 00:24:37.355
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:24:37.355 --> 00:24:38.730
KAI WULFF: Maybe
I can add, there

00:24:38.730 --> 00:24:44.670
were a lot of challenges in
people digging wild boreholes.

00:24:44.670 --> 00:24:47.810
especially affluent
people within the city.

00:24:47.810 --> 00:24:51.740
Like in Nairobi, the
groundwater levels for this

00:24:51.740 --> 00:24:54.290
have dropped tremendously
because everybody

00:24:54.290 --> 00:24:56.970
was drilling a wild borehole.

00:24:56.970 --> 00:25:00.080
And people were drilling
boreholes for irrigation

00:25:00.080 --> 00:25:02.700
purposes, but went
into what's called

00:25:02.700 --> 00:25:05.920
the ice in the salt layers.

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:09.910
So after awhile the
fields become unusable.

00:25:09.910 --> 00:25:14.350
So I have to give kudos
to the Kenyan government

00:25:14.350 --> 00:25:18.730
to be now very
restrictive in not

00:25:18.730 --> 00:25:23.110
just every NGO or every
farmer or everybody

00:25:23.110 --> 00:25:26.790
coming up and just
digging a borehole.

00:25:26.790 --> 00:25:29.910
And there are other areas
where 120 meters is not

00:25:29.910 --> 00:25:32.820
a wild borehole,
that's difficult to do.

00:25:32.820 --> 00:25:35.950
But you have other areas where
the groundwater levels are

00:25:35.950 --> 00:25:41.060
much lower, and you
don't want a scenario

00:25:41.060 --> 00:25:45.730
that the fields get spoiled
by salt content in the ground

00:25:45.730 --> 00:25:48.830
or that the water you
pump out gets contaminated

00:25:48.830 --> 00:25:51.710
by the graveyard next door.

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:55.260
And these were all cases,
actual cases, that happened.

00:25:55.260 --> 00:25:58.560
And, hopefully,
with the involvement

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:00.460
of the communities,
the community,

00:26:00.460 --> 00:26:05.080
itself, if it's educated
will push governments there

00:26:05.080 --> 00:26:09.360
and in other countries
to say, wait a minute,

00:26:09.360 --> 00:26:13.410
it's a good thing, it needs
to be handled in a proper way.

00:26:13.410 --> 00:26:16.600
And if everything happens
transparently and there

00:26:16.600 --> 00:26:22.560
is no, what we call
[? kitu kidogo ?],

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:25.970
a little something
that needs to be paid,

00:26:25.970 --> 00:26:28.770
then this is a very
positive development.

00:26:28.770 --> 00:26:32.900
And, as I said, I'm
usually very skeptical when

00:26:32.900 --> 00:26:35.940
it comes to giving
kudos to government

00:26:35.940 --> 00:26:38.130
regulations
overregulating, but when

00:26:38.130 --> 00:26:41.670
it comes to water sanitation,
natural resources that

00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:44.760
can easily backfire,
that's a very good thing.

00:26:44.760 --> 00:26:47.050
And I have to say, I
looked at the project

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:50.480
and there was a lot of
due diligence done on

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:52.662
not to create those problems.

00:26:52.662 --> 00:26:54.280
AUDIENCE: A follow-up
question to that

00:26:54.280 --> 00:26:58.140
is Kenya has lots of
wonderful resources--

00:26:58.140 --> 00:27:01.350
beautiful oceanfronts,
lakes, it's

00:27:01.350 --> 00:27:03.360
the number one
safari destination

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:06.530
for tourists who come there.

00:27:06.530 --> 00:27:09.530
Anyway, along those lines,
has any consideration--

00:27:09.530 --> 00:27:11.560
I know that the population
doesn't typically

00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:13.470
exist in those
areas, but is there

00:27:13.470 --> 00:27:17.467
any consideration going forward
to desalinization plants that

00:27:17.467 --> 00:27:20.490
could draw from the oceans
or water treatment plants

00:27:20.490 --> 00:27:24.027
could draw from the lakes, or is
this strictly a well endeavor?

00:27:24.027 --> 00:27:25.610
SABORE OLE OYIE:
First of all, I think

00:27:25.610 --> 00:27:32.310
we live about-- to
where I live, I'll

00:27:32.310 --> 00:27:37.160
say 6 or 700 kilometers away
from the sea, very far away.

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:40.890
And we don't have
a lake around us.

00:27:40.890 --> 00:27:47.190
There are a few lakes in Kenya
-- Lake Naivasha, Lake Nakuru,

00:27:47.190 --> 00:27:49.000
Lake Victoria Lake Turkana.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:53.130
There are a few lakes in Kanya,
but we are totally far away.

00:27:53.130 --> 00:27:56.410
We have a river, which is
called the Ewaso Ng'iro.

00:27:56.410 --> 00:27:58.054
There are two Ewaso Ng'iros.

00:27:58.054 --> 00:28:00.470
There is North [INAUDIBLE]
Ewaso Ng'iro and there is South

00:28:00.470 --> 00:28:01.930
[INAUDIBLE] Ewaso Ng'iro.

00:28:01.930 --> 00:28:04.360
And we are in the
South [INAUDIBLE] Ewaso

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:11.480
Ng'iro, and from where I live
it's about seven kilometers

00:28:11.480 --> 00:28:13.060
away from the river.

00:28:13.060 --> 00:28:15.600
So drawing that
water from the river,

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:20.890
it will take a lot of
resources, and cleaning it,

00:28:20.890 --> 00:28:23.680
and trying to purify the water
will take a lot of resources.

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:29.014
So the best thing to
do is the boreholes.

00:28:29.014 --> 00:28:29.958
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:28:29.958 --> 00:28:31.666
SABORE OLE OYIE: And
thank you very much.

00:28:31.666 --> 00:28:34.090
I'm a cultural ambassador
from my country

00:28:34.090 --> 00:28:35.910
so I'm really happy
when you say it's

00:28:35.910 --> 00:28:37.210
one of the best destinations.

00:28:37.210 --> 00:28:39.260
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
is important--

00:28:39.260 --> 00:28:40.850
KAI WULFF: He said
it's the best--

00:28:40.850 --> 00:28:41.933
SABORE OLE OYIE: The best.

00:28:41.933 --> 00:28:44.428
KAI WULFF: --We could never
say that because we're biased,

00:28:44.428 --> 00:28:48.220
but he says it's the best.

00:28:48.220 --> 00:28:50.535
AUDIENCE: I just wondered,
how do you find the world?

00:28:50.535 --> 00:28:53.060
I know in Northern
California they often

00:28:53.060 --> 00:28:56.441
bring these mystical people
out, dowsers with the rod

00:28:56.441 --> 00:28:57.932
and they'll pull
you up and down,

00:28:57.932 --> 00:28:59.920
because they say half the
time the company comes out,

00:28:59.920 --> 00:29:01.162
they can't find it,
they're drilling blind

00:29:01.162 --> 00:29:03.232
even though they've
done some kind of study,

00:29:03.232 --> 00:29:05.280
but these witch
doctors or whatever

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:08.088
can actually half
the time find it.

00:29:08.088 --> 00:29:10.447
How do they find where the
well is in the first place,

00:29:10.447 --> 00:29:13.300
and where to drill?

00:29:13.300 --> 00:29:18.365
SABORE OLE OYIE: Honestly, I'm
not really sure how they do it

00:29:18.365 --> 00:29:21.140
and how they sense it,
but they have metal.

00:29:21.140 --> 00:29:22.620
They use a kind of metal.

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:26.820
This engineer was using a kind
of metal near the machine,

00:29:26.820 --> 00:29:30.790
that he was reading
some numbers,

00:29:30.790 --> 00:29:33.295
and that's how he said that--

00:29:33.295 --> 00:29:37.080
KAI WULFF: Ground electricity
resistance levels.

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:39.580
You can measure
out magnet fields

00:29:39.580 --> 00:29:43.530
that are giving you an
indication where underground

00:29:43.530 --> 00:29:47.150
there should be a flow because
it doesn't help you if you just

00:29:47.150 --> 00:29:50.530
drill down and you
have stale groundwater.

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:52.250
You need to have
some kind of flow.

00:29:52.250 --> 00:29:56.590
So you need earth
underneath with stones

00:29:56.590 --> 00:30:02.310
that allow the movement of
water, because it's a bipole,

00:30:02.310 --> 00:30:03.820
it creates a magnet field.

00:30:03.820 --> 00:30:06.600
And that's the same
principle those guys are

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:10.180
using because they're
very sensible to this.

00:30:10.180 --> 00:30:14.990
My dad and myself we
could do this as a game.

00:30:14.990 --> 00:30:19.900
I wouldn't do it professionally,
but we had a pretty good hit

00:30:19.900 --> 00:30:20.500
rate.

00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:23.900
It's a subconscious thing.

00:30:23.900 --> 00:30:26.710
People or animals
react to magnet fields.

00:30:26.710 --> 00:30:29.070
It's no magic involved with it.

00:30:29.070 --> 00:30:31.870
It's simply that you
have to believe in it,

00:30:31.870 --> 00:30:34.668
and you have to be
loose enough to do it.

00:30:34.668 --> 00:30:37.945
AUDIENCE: In followup,
are there any issues

00:30:37.945 --> 00:30:40.344
with the well going dry?

00:30:40.344 --> 00:30:42.774
How do you know that there's
enough water there every year

00:30:42.774 --> 00:30:47.148
for 100 years, will there be
water, or is that an issue?

00:30:47.148 --> 00:30:51.036
If the well goes dry [INAUDIBLE]
do something like that?

00:30:51.036 --> 00:30:53.920
SABORE OLE OYIE: I think that
one will depend, actually,

00:30:53.920 --> 00:30:57.290
on the usage of water.

00:30:57.290 --> 00:31:00.560
And how much is the
water being used,

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:06.210
and how much you have gone deep
to the where the source is.

00:31:06.210 --> 00:31:08.660
Because, according to
the report, he said

00:31:08.660 --> 00:31:12.890
there are 8,000
liters in one hour.

00:31:12.890 --> 00:31:14.140
I think that is enough for us.

00:31:14.140 --> 00:31:18.440
So we believe in-- you
never know about nature.

00:31:18.440 --> 00:31:21.570
You cannot predict
when it's going to end,

00:31:21.570 --> 00:31:25.283
but we believe it's going
to last for a long time.

00:31:25.283 --> 00:31:27.782
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering,
considering this a community

00:31:27.782 --> 00:31:31.618
effort, what kind of
individual participation

00:31:31.618 --> 00:31:33.980
are you looking
at for people that

00:31:33.980 --> 00:31:35.328
are not based in the community?

00:31:39.442 --> 00:31:41.950
SABORE OLE OYIE:
Mostly what we like

00:31:41.950 --> 00:31:48.680
is we will appreciate the
advise, like people like Kai,

00:31:48.680 --> 00:31:51.730
to be able to come and give
us an advice on what can we

00:31:51.730 --> 00:31:53.450
do in the future.

00:31:53.450 --> 00:31:57.720
And I think when you're also
constructing the borehole,

00:31:57.720 --> 00:32:02.840
we also need people to come and
help volunteer and do something

00:32:02.840 --> 00:32:08.490
to be able to help us building
the structure of the house,

00:32:08.490 --> 00:32:19.620
and also giving us advice
on how to maintain.

00:32:19.620 --> 00:32:23.520
And mostly is on how
we can get the fundings

00:32:23.520 --> 00:32:26.260
for the next project.

00:32:26.260 --> 00:32:28.250
KAI WULFF: I would give
you a business case.

00:32:28.250 --> 00:32:32.720
Open a little tent camp
for volunteers to come over

00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:36.790
and help with the work, and
sell the spaces in the tent camp

00:32:36.790 --> 00:32:40.110
and then be a moving
camp and a builder.

00:32:40.110 --> 00:32:43.470
So you never know.

00:32:43.470 --> 00:32:46.120
Everything is driven
by business in the end.

00:32:46.120 --> 00:32:47.515
AUDIENCE: Absolutely.

00:32:47.515 --> 00:32:50.340
KAI WULFF: I would
like to say thank you

00:32:50.340 --> 00:32:54.740
for everybody that's worked
very, very hard on the project.

00:32:54.740 --> 00:32:57.980
I think Sabore has
a few things to sell

00:32:57.980 --> 00:33:01.730
that support the cause as well.

00:33:01.730 --> 00:33:05.110
And I'm very, very happy
to be aligned with it

00:33:05.110 --> 00:33:07.790
and to help with
advice and whatever

00:33:07.790 --> 00:33:10.075
else I can do for
my old home, Kenya.

00:33:10.075 --> 00:33:11.200
SABORE OLE OYIE: Thank you.

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:12.033
Thank you very much.

00:33:12.033 --> 00:33:15.040
Thank you very much
for coming, and we also

00:33:15.040 --> 00:33:19.870
